the-back-of-an-air-ticket/15972/1?id=15972&pg=1 |newspaper=[[Forbes]] |location=India |publisher=[[Forbes (India)|Forbesindia.com]] |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Past===\n====Committee memberships====\n* Chair, Committee for Asset Valuation and Principles of Disposal of Corporate Properties, Assets and Shares; Indian government [[Ministry of Corporate Affairs]]\n* Chair, Review of Offences and Penalties under the Company Law; Indian government Ministry of Corporate Affairs\n* 1996{{ndash}}Dr. Jamshed J. Irani Committee for amending [[The Companies Act, 1956]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.primedirectors.com/pdf/JJ%20Irani%20Report-MCA.pdf |title=Report on Company Law |last=Irani |first=Dr. Jamshed J. |date=31 May 2005 |website=primedirectors.com |publisher=Prime Database / [[National Stock Exchange of India]] Ltd. (NSE) / BSE (The Stock Exchange Investors' Protection Fund) |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>\n* 1996\u201397, 2000{{ndash}}[[Securities and Exchange Board of India]] (SEBI)-appointed Bhagwati Committees for redrafting and modifying the SEBI Takeover Code\n* Confederation of Indian Industry (CII) Task Force on Corporate Governance, which drafted the ''Corporate Governance Recommendations for Voluntary Adoption'' by directors<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mca.gov.in/Ministry/latestnews/Draft_Report_NareshChandra_CII.pdf |title=Corporate Governance Recommendations for Voluntary Adoption |last=Chandra |first=Naresh |date=November 2009 |website=[[Ministry of Corporate Affairs]], Government of India |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>\n* second [[Naresh Chandra]] Committee appointed to look into aspects of small and medium enterprise and simplification of Company Law (LLPs and joint ventures)\n* Dr. [[Amit Mitra]] Committee, appointed by the [[Ministry of Information and Broadcasting (India)|Ministry of Information and Broadcasting]] to revamp Radio Broadcast Policy, to recommend changes to license conditions for privatisation of the radio sector, and to propose a national broadcast regulator\n* [[M. Damodaran]] \u2013 [[FICCI|Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FICCI)]] Committee on [[Corporate Governance]]\n\n===Current===\n\n====Bar memberships====\n* [[Supreme Court Bar Association of India]]\n* Delhi Bar Association\n* [[International Bar Association]] (IBA)\n\nHe is an [[Advocates-on-Record|advocate-on-record]] of the [[Supreme Court of India]].\n\n==Affiliations==\nShroff is Associate President of [[Society of Indian Law Firms]] (SILF),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.silf.org.in/4/Office-Bearers-and-Executive-Committee.htm |title=SILF \u2013 Office Bearers & Executive Committee |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | website=SILF [[Society of Indian Law Firms]] |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> a collective of India\u2019s top corporate law firms that has opposed entry of foreign law firms into India.<ref>{{cite news |last=Venkatesan |first=J. |date=27 July 2010 |title=Entry of foreign law firms opposed |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/entry-of-foreign-law-firms-opposed/article535339.ece |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShardul Shroff is a grandson of Amarchand Shroff, who founded the law firm \"[[Amarchand & Mangaldas & Suresh A Shroff & Co]]\" in 1917. He is a son of Suresh A. Shroff, a former managing partner of the firm and Bharati Shroff, also the co-owner of the firm.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dispute over will rocks law firm Amarchand Mangaldas; Shardul & Cyril Shroff in legal battle over assets|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-11-15/news/56115231_1_law-firm-amarchand-mangaldas-suresh-a-shroff-co|accessdate=16 December 2014|publisher=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Bharti Shroff, the old firm was split into two with Shardul heading the Shardul Amarchand Mangaldas and brother Cyril Shroff heading the [[Cyril Amarchand Mangaldas]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Amarchand & Mangaldas: Understanding the Shardul versus Cyril Shroff battle|url=http://www.moneylife.in/article/amarchand-mangaldas-understanding-the-shardul-versus-cyril-shroff-battle/39529.html|website=Moneylife|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nShroff is married to [[Pallavi Shroff]], an advocate and daughter of former [[Chief Justice of India]], [[Prafullachandra Natwarlal Bhagwati|PN Bhagwati]]. They have two daughters, Shweta Shroff and [[Natashaa Shroff]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shroff, Shardul S.}}\n[[Category:20th-century Indian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n{{India-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAffiliations:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shardul_S._Shroff"}
{"title_page": "Jaiprakashreddy Patil", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=May 2017}}\n{{more footnotes|date=March 2017|blp=yes}}\n{{Like resume|date=July 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Jaiprakashreddy Patil\n| image             =\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1954|3|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Karnataka, India]]\n| nationality       = [[India]]\n| workplaces        = [[National Law University and Judicial Academy, Assam]] \n| awards            = TCS- Education World Best Teacher Merit Award (2005)\n}}\n\n'''Prof. J.S. Patil''' is a Professor of Law and currently the Vice-Chancellor of [[National Law University and Judicial Academy, Assam]]. He was the Founder Vice-Chancellor of Karnataka State Law University, Hubli, 2009\u201312.\n\n==Early life and education==\n'''Jaiprakashreddy Sannabasanagouda Patil''' was born in an agriculturist family at [[Manvi]], [[Raichur district]], [[Karnataka]]. He qualified in law from [[Karnataka University]], Dharwad in 1977, and pursued LL.M. from the [[University of Mysore]], and earned his master's degree in 1979. He received his Ph.D from [[Saurashtra University]], [[Rajkot]] in 1997.\n\n== Books and publications ==\n\n* Legal Regime of the Seabed, 1981, Deep & Deep Publications, New Delhi\n* Gramina Janate Mattu Kanunu, Prasaranga, Gulbarga University, Kalaburagi\n* Tulanatmaka Kanunu, 1995, Vidyanidhi Prakashana, Gadag\n* Mahile Mattu Kanunu, 1996, Prasaranga Gulbarga University, Kalaburagi\n* Nyaya Shastra Adhyayana, 1996 Ramashraya publications, Dharwad\n* Bhrata Sakshya Adhiniyama, 1996 Ramashraya Publications, Dharwad\n* Karnataka Bhu-Sudharane Adhiniyama, 1996, Ramashraya Publications, Dharwad\n* Karnataka Diwani Vyavaharanegala Niyamagalu, 1997, Ramashraya Publications, Dharwad\n* \"Sri Gangadhar Namoshi\", a book published by the Government of Karnataka\n* Spirit of Human Rights, A Manual, 2005, published by National Human Rights Commission, New Delhi\n* Intellectual Property Rights, A Manual, 2005, published by Siddhartha Law College, Kalaburagi\n\n==References==\n{{Cite web|url=http://www.gulbargauniversity.kar.nic.in/FacLaw/profile/LawJSPatil.html|title=Dr. J.S. Patil, Dept. of Law, GUG|website=www.gulbargauniversity.kar.nic.in}}\n\n{{Cite web|url=http://www.legallyindia.com/lawschools/nlu-assam-gets-new-vc-from-k-taka-u-js-patil-to-focus-on-campus-local-laws-20161002-8014|title=NLU Assam gets new VC from K\u2019taka U: JS Patil to focus on campus, local laws|last=Ganz|first=Kian|website=www.legallyindia.com|language=en-gb}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nluassam.ac.in/vcdesk.htm From the Vice Chancellor's Desk]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patil, Jaiprakashreddy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Karnatak University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Mysore alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian lawyers]]\n\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=May 2017}}\n{{more footnotes|date=March 2017|blp=yes}}\n{{Like resume|date=July 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Jaiprakashreddy Patil\n| image             =\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1954|3|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Karnataka, India]]\n| nationality       = [[India]]\n| workplaces        = [[National Law University and Judicial Academy, Assam]] \n| awards            = TCS- Education World Best Teacher Merit Award (2005)\n}}\n\n'''Prof. J.S. Patil''' is a Professor of Law and currently the Vice-Chancellor of [[National Law University and Judicial Academy, Assam]]. He was the Founder Vice-Chancellor of Karnataka State Law University, Hubli, 2009-12.\n\n==Early life and education==\n'''Jaiprakashreddy Sannabasanagouda Patil''' was born in an agriculturist family at [[Manvi]], [[Raichur district]], [[Karnataka]]. He qualified in law from [[Karnataka University]], Dharwad in 1977, and pursued LL.M. from the [[University of Mysore]], and earned his master's degree in 1979. He received his Ph.D from [[Saurashtra University]], [[Rajkot]] in 1997.\n\n== Books and publications ==\n\n* Legal Regime of the Seabed, 1981, Deep & Deep Publications, New Delhi\n* Gramina Janate Mattu Kanunu, Prasaranga, Gulbarga University, Kalaburagi\n* Tulanatmaka Kanunu, 1995, Vidyanidhi Prakashana, Gadag\n* Mahile Mattu Kanunu, 1996, Prasaranga Gulbarga University, Kalaburagi\n* Nyaya Shastra Adhyayana, 1996 Ramashraya publications, Dharwad\n* Bhrata Sakshya Adhiniyama, 1996 Ramashraya Publications, Dharwad\n* Karnataka Bhu-Sudharane Adhiniyama, 1996, Ramashraya Publications, Dharwad\n* Karnataka Diwani Vyavaharanegala Niyamagalu, 1997, Ramashraya Publications, Dharwad\n* \"Sri Gangadhar Namoshi\", a book published by the Government of Karnataka\n* Spirit of Human Rights, A Manual, 2005, published by National Human Rights Commission, New Delhi\n* Intellectual Property Rights, A Manual, 2005, published by Siddhartha Law College, Kalaburagi\n\n==References==\n{{Cite web|url=http://www.gulbargauniversity.kar.nic.in/FacLaw/profile/LawJSPatil.html|title=Dr. J.S. Patil, Dept. of Law, GUG|website=www.gulbargauniversity.kar.nic.in}}\n\n{{Cite web|url=http://www.legallyindia.com/lawschools/nlu-assam-gets-new-vc-from-k-taka-u-js-patil-to-focus-on-campus-local-laws-20161002-8014|title=NLU Assam gets new VC from K\u2019taka U: JS Patil to focus on campus, local laws|last=Ganz|first=Kian|website=www.legallyindia.com|language=en-gb}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nluassam.ac.in/vcdesk.htm From the Vice Chancellor's Desk]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patil, Jaiprakashreddy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Karnatak University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Mysore alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian lawyers]]\n\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2009-12 \u2192 2009\u201312", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jaiprakashreddy_Patil"}
{"title_page": "Francis du Pr\u00e9 Oldfield", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2018}}\n'''Sir Francis du Pr\u00e9 Oldfield''' (30 June 1869 \u2013 14 February 1928)<ref name=\"cambridge\">{{cite book |title=Cambridge University Alumni, 1261-1900}}</ref> was an English magistrate who was a Judge of the High Court of Judicature, Madras. He was knighted in 1923.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |title= Sir Francis Oldfield|work=[[The Times]] |publisher=The Times Digital Archive |page=19  |date=16 February 1928}}</ref>\n\nOldfield was born in [[Stamford, Lincolnshire]], the son of Rev. Canon Charles Oldfield. He was educated at [[Marlborough College]]  and [[Trinity College, Cambridge]]. In 1890, he entered the [[Indian Civil Service]]. He became a Joint Magistrate in 1904, a District and Session Judge in Madras in 1908, and Puisne Judge of the High Court of Madras, 1913\u201324. He retired in 1924 and returned to England, where from 1924\u201328, he was professor of [[jurisprudence]] at the [[University of Manchester]].<ref name=\"cambridge\"/><ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nHe married Frances Sophia Henrietta Cayley, daughter of Sir [[Richard Cayley]]. He died of pneumonia in Manchester in 1928.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oldfield, Francis}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:British judges]]\n[[Category:Indian Civil Service (British India) officers]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Madras High Court]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marlborough College]]\n[[Category:People from Stamford, Lincolnshire]]\n\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2018}}\n'''Sir Francis du Pr\u00e9 Oldfield''' (30 June 1869 \u2013 14 February 1928)<ref name=\"cambridge\">{{cite book |title=Cambridge University Alumni, 1261-1900}}</ref> was an English magistrate who was a Judge of the High Court of Judicature, Madras. He was knighted in 1923.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |title= Sir Francis Oldfield|work=[[The Times]] |publisher=The Times Digital Archive |page=19  |date=16 February 1928}}</ref>\n\nOldfield was born in [[Stamford, Lincolnshire]], the son of Rev. Canon Charles Oldfield. He was educated at [[Marlborough College]]  and [[Trinity College, Cambridge]]. In 1890, he entered the [[Indian Civil Service]]. He became a Joint Magistrate in 1904, a District and Session Judge in Madras in 1908, and Puisne Judge of the High Court of Madras, 1913-24. He retired in 1924 and returned to England, where from 1924\u201328, he was professor of [[jurisprudence]] at the [[University of Manchester]].<ref name=\"cambridge\"/><ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nHe married Frances Sophia Henrietta Cayley, daughter of Sir [[Richard Cayley]]. He died of pneumonia in Manchester in 1928.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oldfield, Francis}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:British judges]]\n[[Category:Indian Civil Service (British India) officers]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Madras High Court]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marlborough College]]\n[[Category:People from Stamford, Lincolnshire]]\n\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1913-24 \u2192 1913\u201324", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_du_Pr%C3%A9_Oldfield"}
{"title_page": "Nishita Nirmal Mhatre", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n'''Nishita Nirmal Mhatre''' was the Acting Chief Justice of [[Calcutta High Court]] in India. She joined office on 1 December 2016 and retired as the acting chief justice of the [[Calcutta High Court]] on 18 September 2017. During her tenure as the Acting Chief justice, she presided over the high-profile sting operation of the [[Trinamool Congress]] leaders popularly known as the [[Narada sting operation|Narada case]] and ordered [[Central Bureau of Investigation|CBI]] investigation in that case.\n\n== Early life ==\nShe was born on 20 September 1955 and completed schooling from St. Mary's School Pune. Graduated from [[Sophia College for Women|Sophia College]], [[Mumbai]] with Microbiology. Mhatre Graduated in Law from Government Law College, Mumbai.\n\n== Legal profession ==\nEnrolled as an Advocate on the rolls of Bar Council of Maharashtra and Goa on 10 November 1978. After that she practised in the Industrial Tribunal and Labour Court, Motor Accidents Claims Tribunal and the [[Bombay High Court]].\nSworn-in as an Additional Judge of the High Court of Judicature at Bombay on 28 March 2001. She became a Permanent Judge of the High Court of Judicature at Bombay on 21 March 2003. Mhatre was transferred to the High Court at Calcutta (vide, Notification dated 27 December 2011) and was sworn in as a Judge of this Court on 6 January 2012.\nShe was appointed as Acting Chief Justice of the Calcutta High Court on 1 December 2016 after the retirement of the Chief Justice [[Girish Chandra Gupta]]<ref>[http://calcuttahighcourt.nic.in/bio/nishita_mhatre.html  Calcutta High Court] {{dead link|date=August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.livelaw.in/justice-nishita-nirmal-mhatre-become-acting-chief-justice-calcutta-hc/ |title=Justice Nishita Nirmal Mhatre to become Acting Chief Justice of Calcutta HC|date=25 November 2016 |website=LiveLaw.in}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indian women judges]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Kolkata High Court]]\n\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n'''Nishita Nirmal Mhatre''' was the Acting Chief Justice of [[Calcutta High Court]] in India. She joined office on 1 December 2016 and retired as the acting chief justice of the [[Calcutta High Court]] on 18 September 2017. During her tenure as the Acting Chief justice, she presided over the high-profile sting operation of the [[Trinamool Congress]] leaders popularly known as the [[Narada sting operation|Narada case]] and ordered [[Central Bureau of Investigation|CBI]] investigation in that case.\n\n== Early life ==\nShe was born on 20 September 1955 and completed schooling from St. Mary\u2019s School Pune. Graduated from [[Sophia College for Women|Sophia College]], [[Mumbai]] with Microbiology. Mhatre Graduated in Law from Government Law College, Mumbai.\n\n== Legal profession ==\nEnrolled as an Advocate on the rolls of Bar Council of Maharashtra and Goa on 10 November 1978. After that she practised in the Industrial Tribunal and Labour Court, Motor Accidents Claims Tribunal and the [[Bombay High Court]].\nSworn-in as an Additional Judge of the High Court of Judicature at Bombay on 28 March 2001. She became a Permanent Judge of the High Court of Judicature at Bombay on 21 March 2003. Mhatre was transferred to the High Court at Calcutta (vide, Notification dated 27 December 2011) and was sworn in as a Judge of this Court on 6 January 2012.\nShe was appointed as Acting Chief Justice of the Calcutta High Court on 1 December 2016 after the retirement of the Chief Justice [[Girish Chandra Gupta]]<ref>[http://calcuttahighcourt.nic.in/bio/nishita_mhatre.html  Calcutta High Court] {{dead link|date=August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.livelaw.in/justice-nishita-nirmal-mhatre-become-acting-chief-justice-calcutta-hc/ |title=Justice Nishita Nirmal Mhatre to become Acting Chief Justice of Calcutta HC|date=25 November 2016 |website=LiveLaw.in}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indian women judges]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Kolkata High Court]]\n\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nishita_Nirmal_Mhatre"}
{"title_page": "Ranganath Misra", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name          = Ranganath Mishra\n| image         = Ranganath Mishra.png\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n|office =[[Member of Parliament]], [[Rajya Sabha]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/former-cji-ranganath-mishra-dead/775153 | title=Former CJI Ranganath Mishra Dead | publisher=Outlook | date=13 September 2012 | accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n| termstart     = 1998\n| termend       = 2004\n|constituency  = [[Odisha]]\n| order1         = 21st\n| office1        = Chief Justice of India\n| termstart1     = 25 September 1990\n| termend1       = 24 November 1991\n| nominator1     = \n| appointer1     = [[Ramaswamy Venkataraman]]\n| predecessor1   = [[Sabyasachi Mukharji]]\n| successor1     = [[Kamal Narain Singh]]\n|office2      = 1st chairman [[National Human Rights Commission of India|National Human Rights Commission]]\n|term_start2 = 12 October 1993\n|term_end2    = 24 November 1996\n|predecessor2= \n|successor2  = \n| office4      = [[Governor of Odisha]]\n| term4 = 25 June 1982 - 31 August 1982\n| predecessor4 = [[Cheppudira Muthana Poonacha]]\n| successor4     = [[Cheppudira Muthana Poonacha]]\n|party = [[Indian National Congress]] <ref>{{cite web | url=https://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/pre_member/1952_2003/m.pdf | title=RAJYA SABHA MEMBERS BIOGRAPHICAL SKETCHES 1952 - 2003 | publisher=[[Rajya Sabha]] | accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1926|11|25}}\n|birth_place    = [[Banapur]], [[Odisha]]\n|death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=y|2012|09|13|1926|11|25}}\n|death_place    = [[Bhubaneswar]], Odisha\n| spouse        = \n|alma_mater     = [[Ravenshaw College]]<br/>[[Allahabad University]]\n}}\n'''Ranganath Mishra''' (25 November 1926 \u2013 13 September 2012) was as the 21st [[Chief Justice of India]], serving from 25 September 1990 to 24 November 1991. He was also the first chairman of the [[National Human Rights Commission (India)|National Human Rights Commission of India]].<ref name=\"NHRC release\">{{cite web |title=Curtain Raiser for Foundation Day on October. 12, 2006 |url=http://nhrc.nic.in/disparchive.asp?fno=1301 |publisher=[[National Human Rights Commission (India)]] |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> He also served as Member of Parliament in Rajya Sabha from the [[Indian National Congress|Congress Party]] between 1998\u20132004.He is the second Supreme court judge to became a [[Rajya Sabha]] member after [[Baharul Islam]]  who  was also elected as [[Indian National Congress]] member.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://theprint.in/india/former-cji-ranjan-gogoi-nominated-to-rajya-sabha-less-than-6-months-after-retirement/382089/ | title=Former CJI Ranjan Gogoi nominated to Rajya Sabha, less than 6 months after retirement | publisher=ThePrint | work=Debayon Roy | date=16 March 2020 | accessdate=16  March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background and family==\nRanganath Misra was born on 25 November 1926 in [[Banapur]], [[Odisha]] into an Odia Brahmin family. His father, [[Godavaris Mishra]] (sometimes spelt Godabarish Misra), was an Odia litterateur and congress politician who became education minister of Orissa state in 1941 while India was still under British rule. In this capacity, Godavaris was instrumental in the founding of [[Utkal University]].\n\nRanganath was the youngest of three sons. His eldest brother, [[Lokanath Misra]], was a prominent politician belonging to [[Swatantra Party]] (led by [[Rajaji]]) and later the [[Janata Party]]. He served for several terms as a member of the [[Rajya Sabha]] (upper house of Indian parliament) and also as governor of [[Assam]] and [[Nagaland]]. Loknath Misra's son, [[Pinaki Misra]], is a [[Lok Sabha]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] belonging to the [[Biju Janata Dal]]. Ranganath's second brother, Raghunath Misra, was a politician belonging to the [[Indian National Congress|Congress Party]] who was elected to the Orissa Legislative Assembly from the Banpur constituency. Raghunath's son, [[Dipak Misra]] was the 45th [[Chief Justice of India]]; he was in office from 28 August 2017 to 2 October 2018.\n\nRanganath studied in Banpur High School and P.M. Academy and later at [[Ravenshaw College]] and [[Allahabad University]]. At a young age, he was married to Sumitra Misra, a woman of his own community and similar background. In 1950, they had a son, Devananda Misra, who became a lawyer and a senior advocate in the Supreme Court and the Orissa High Court. Devananda died in 2009, aged 59.\n\n==Legal career==\nOn 18 September 1950 he got enrolled as advocate of [[Orissa High Court]], [[Cuttack]] where he practiced law until 1969 when he was appointed as a Permanent Judge of the Orissa High Court. From 6 November 1980 to 16 January 1981 he was appointed as the acting Chief Justice of Orissa High Court, and from 16 January 1981 he was appointed as the permanent Chief Justice of the Orissa High court. He was then appointed Judge of the [[Supreme Court of India]] in 1983. He became the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of India on 25 September 1990 and retired on 24 November 1991.\n\n==1984 anti-Sikh riots==\nRanganath Misra was the sole member of the Justice Ranganath Misra Commission of Inquiry, a commission that headed the investigation of [[1984 anti-Sikh riots]] and produced a report. [[Jagjit Singh Aurora]], the former [[General Officer Commanding|General Officer Commanding-in-Chief]] of the [[Indian Army]] and a member of the [[Citizen's Justice Committee]], commented that \"The terms of reference of the commission were biased against the victims, the victims were forced to come to the investigation with the burden of proof on them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/indiascope/story/19860430-justice-mishra-commission-report-on-1984-anti-sikhs-riots-may-find-few-takers-800825-1986-04-30|title=Justice Mishra Commission report on 1984 anti-Sikhs riots may find few takers|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref> He indicted 19 workers of the Congress Party who were charged by the [[People's Union for Civil Liberties]] of having abetted the riots, but gave clean chit to the Congress Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/special-report/story/19900131-rajivs-government-set-up-one-member-justice-ranganath-misra-commission-of-inquiry-812267-1990-01-31|title=Rajiv's government set up one-member Justice Ranganath Misra Commission of Inquiry|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2005/feb/18spec1.htm|title=The lessons of 1984|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement and death==\nHe served as the [[Chief Scout (India)|Chief Scout]] of the [[All India Boy Scouts Association]] since 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lawbookshop.net/hindu-usage-p-300.html|title=Law Book Shop}}</ref> He became the first Chairman of the [[National Human Rights Commission of India]] in 1993. He was member of Rajya Sabha from 1998 to 2004 from the Congress Party headed by Sonia Gandhi.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://164.100.47.5:8080/members/alphabeticallist_all_terms.asp?alphabet=M |title=Alphabetical List Of All Members Of Rajya Sabha Since 1952 |quote=Misra Shri Ranganath Odisha INC 02/07/1998 01/07/2004 |accessdate=30 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter prolonged illness, Rangnath Misra died on 13 September 2012 at a private hospital in [[Bhubaneswar]]. He was survived by his wife Sumitra Misra and grandson Anand Misra.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ranganath Misra passes away |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article3893788.ece |work=The Hindu |date=14 September 2012 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120511112344/http://supremecourtofindia.nic.in/judges/rcji/21rmisra.htm Supreme Court of India: Hon'ble Mr. Justice Raganath Misra.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-legal}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Chief Justice of India]]\n| before= [[Sabyasachi Mukharji]]\n| after= [[Kamal Narain Singh]]\n| years=1990&ndash;1991}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{succession box |\n  | title = [[List of Governors of Odisha|Governor of Odisha]]|\n  | years = 25 June 1982 - 31 August 1982\n  | before = [[Cheppudira Muthanna Poonacha]]|\n  | after = [[Cheppudira Muthanna Poonacha]]|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chief Justices of India}}\n{{Rajya Sabha Members from Orissa}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misra, Ranganath}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scouting and Guiding in India]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of India]]\n[[Category:People from Khordha district]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Odisha]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Odisha]]\n\n{{scout-bio-stub}}\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n{{Odisha-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name          = Ranganath Mishra\n| image         = Ranganath Mishra.png\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n|office =[[Member of Parliament]], [[Rajya Sabha]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/former-cji-ranganath-mishra-dead/775153 | title=Former CJI Ranganath Mishra Dead | publisher=Outlook | date=13 September 2012 | accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n| termstart     = 1998\n| termend       = 2004\n|constituency  = [[Odisha]]\n| order1         = 21st\n| office1        = Chief Justice of India\n| termstart1     = 25 September 1990\n| termend1       = 24 November 1991\n| nominator1     = \n| appointer1     = [[Ramaswamy Venkataraman]]\n| predecessor1   = [[Sabyasachi Mukharji]]\n| successor1     = [[Kamal Narain Singh]]\n|office2      = 1st chairman [[National Human Rights Commission of India|National Human Rights Commission]]\n|term_start2 = 12 October 1993\n|term_end2    = 24 November 1996\n|predecessor2= \n|successor2  = \n| office4      = [[Governor of Odisha]]\n| term4 = 25 June 1982 - 31 August 1982\n| predecessor4 = [[Cheppudira Muthana Poonacha]]\n| successor4     = [[Cheppudira Muthana Poonacha]]\n|party = [[Indian National Congress]] <ref>{{cite web | url=https://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/pre_member/1952_2003/m.pdf | title=RAJYA SABHA MEMBERS BIOGRAPHICAL SKETCHES 1952 - 2003 | publisher=[[Rajya Sabha]] | accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1926|11|25}}\n|birth_place    = [[Banapur]], [[Odisha]]\n|death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=y|2012|09|13|1926|11|25}}\n|death_place    = [[Bhubaneswar]], Odisha\n| spouse        = \n|alma_mater     = [[Ravenshaw College]]<br/>[[Allahabad University]]\n}}\n'''Ranganath Mishra''' (25 November 1926 \u2013 13 September 2012) was as the 21st [[Chief Justice of India]], serving from 25 September 1990 to 24 November 1991. He was also the first chairman of the [[National Human Rights Commission (India)|National Human Rights Commission of India]].<ref name=\"NHRC release\">{{cite web |title=Curtain Raiser for Foundation Day on October. 12, 2006 |url=http://nhrc.nic.in/disparchive.asp?fno=1301 |publisher=[[National Human Rights Commission (India)]] |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> He also served as Member of Parliament in Rajya Sabha from the [[Indian National Congress|Congress Party]] between 1998-2004.He is the second Supreme court judge to became a [[Rajya Sabha]] member after [[Baharul Islam]]  who  was also elected as [[Indian National Congress]] member.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://theprint.in/india/former-cji-ranjan-gogoi-nominated-to-rajya-sabha-less-than-6-months-after-retirement/382089/ | title=Former CJI Ranjan Gogoi nominated to Rajya Sabha, less than 6 months after retirement | publisher=ThePrint | work=Debayon Roy | date=16 March 2020 | accessdate=16  March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background and family==\nRanganath Misra was born on 25 November 1926 in [[Banapur]], [[Odisha]] into an Odia Brahmin family. His father, [[Godavaris Mishra]] (sometimes spelt Godabarish Misra), was an Odia litterateur and congress politician who became education minister of Orissa state in 1941 while India was still under British rule. In this capacity, Godavaris was instrumental in the founding of [[Utkal University]].\n\nRanganath was the youngest of three sons. His eldest brother, [[Lokanath Misra]], was a prominent politician belonging to [[Swatantra Party]] (led by [[Rajaji]]) and later the [[Janata Party]]. He served for several terms as a member of the [[Rajya Sabha]] (upper house of Indian parliament) and also as governor of [[Assam]] and [[Nagaland]]. Loknath Misra's son, [[Pinaki Misra]], is a [[Lok Sabha]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] belonging to the [[Biju Janata Dal]]. Ranganath's second brother, Raghunath Misra, was a politician belonging to the [[Indian National Congress|Congress Party]] who was elected to the Orissa Legislative Assembly from the Banpur constituency. Raghunath's son, [[Dipak Misra]] was the 45th [[Chief Justice of India]]; he was in office from 28 August 2017 to 2 October 2018.\n\nRanganath studied in Banpur High School and P.M. Academy and later at [[Ravenshaw College]] and [[Allahabad University]]. At a young age, he was married to Sumitra Misra, a woman of his own community and similar background. In 1950, they had a son, Devananda Misra, who became a lawyer and a senior advocate in the Supreme Court and the Orissa High Court. Devananda died in 2009, aged 59.\n\n==Legal career==\nOn 18 September 1950 he got enrolled as advocate of [[Orissa High Court]], [[Cuttack]] where he practiced law until 1969 when he was appointed as a Permanent Judge of the Orissa High Court. From 6 November 1980 to 16 January 1981 he was appointed as the acting Chief Justice of Orissa High Court, and from 16 January 1981 he was appointed as the permanent Chief Justice of the Orissa High court. He was then appointed Judge of the [[Supreme Court of India]] in 1983. He became the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of India on 25 September 1990 and retired on 24 November 1991.\n\n==1984 anti-Sikh riots==\nRanganath Misra was the sole member of the Justice Ranganath Misra Commission of Inquiry, a commission that headed the investigation of [[1984 anti-Sikh riots]] and produced a report. [[Jagjit Singh Aurora]], the former [[General Officer Commanding|General Officer Commanding-in-Chief]] of the [[Indian Army]] and a member of the [[Citizen's Justice Committee]], commented that \"The terms of reference of the commission were biased against the victims, the victims were forced to come to the investigation with the burden of proof on them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/indiascope/story/19860430-justice-mishra-commission-report-on-1984-anti-sikhs-riots-may-find-few-takers-800825-1986-04-30|title=Justice Mishra Commission report on 1984 anti-Sikhs riots may find few takers|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref> He indicted 19 workers of the Congress Party who were charged by the [[People's Union for Civil Liberties]] of having abetted the riots, but gave clean chit to the Congress Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/special-report/story/19900131-rajivs-government-set-up-one-member-justice-ranganath-misra-commission-of-inquiry-812267-1990-01-31|title=Rajiv's government set up one-member Justice Ranganath Misra Commission of Inquiry|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2005/feb/18spec1.htm|title=The lessons of 1984|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement and death==\nHe served as the [[Chief Scout (India)|Chief Scout]] of the [[All India Boy Scouts Association]] since 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lawbookshop.net/hindu-usage-p-300.html|title=Law Book Shop}}</ref> He became the first Chairman of the [[National Human Rights Commission of India]] in 1993. He was member of Rajya Sabha from 1998 to 2004 from the Congress Party headed by Sonia Gandhi.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://164.100.47.5:8080/members/alphabeticallist_all_terms.asp?alphabet=M |title=Alphabetical List Of All Members Of Rajya Sabha Since 1952 |quote=Misra Shri Ranganath Odisha INC 02/07/1998 01/07/2004 |accessdate=30 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter prolonged illness, Rangnath Misra died on 13 September 2012 at a private hospital in [[Bhubaneswar]]. He was survived by his wife Sumitra Misra and grandson Anand Misra.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ranganath Misra passes away |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article3893788.ece |work=The Hindu |date=14 September 2012 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120511112344/http://supremecourtofindia.nic.in/judges/rcji/21rmisra.htm Supreme Court of India: Hon'ble Mr. Justice Raganath Misra.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-legal}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Chief Justice of India]]\n| before= [[Sabyasachi Mukharji]]\n| after= [[Kamal Narain Singh]]\n| years=1990&ndash;1991}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{succession box |\n  | title = [[List of Governors of Odisha|Governor of Odisha]]|\n  | years = 25 June 1982 - 31 August 1982\n  | before = [[Cheppudira Muthanna Poonacha]]|\n  | after = [[Cheppudira Muthanna Poonacha]]|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chief Justices of India}}\n{{Rajya Sabha Members from Orissa}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misra, Ranganath}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scouting and Guiding in India]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of India]]\n[[Category:People from Khordha district]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Odisha]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Odisha]]\n\n{{scout-bio-stub}}\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n{{Odisha-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1998-2004 \u2192 1998\u20132004", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranganath_Misra"}
{"title_page": "Mehr Chand Mahajan", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Justice Mehr Chand Mahajan\n| office              = Chief Justice of India\n| order               = 3rd\n| honorific-prefix    = The Honourable\n| honorific-suffix    = \n| image               = Justice_Mehr_Chand_Mahajan.jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| appointer           = [[Rajendra Prasad]]\n| predecessor         = [[M. Patanjali Sastri]]\n| successor           = [[Bijan Kumar Mukherjea]]\n| birth_place         = [[Kangra district|Kangra]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[British Raj|British India]]<br><small>(now in [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[India]])</small>\n| death_date          = 1967\n| website             = http://www.mehrchandmahajan.org\n| term_start          = 4 January 1954\n| term_end            = 22 December 1954\n| term_start2         = 15 October 1947\n| term_end2           = 5 March 1948\n| Son                 = Vikram Mahajan\n}}\n\n'''Justice Mehr Chand Mahajan''' (23 December 1889 in [[Nagrota]], [[Kangra district]] \u2013 1967) was the third Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of India]]. Prior to that he was the [[Dewan]] of [[Jammu and Kashmir]] during the reign of Maharaja [[Hari Singh]] and played a key role in the accession of J&K to [[India]]. He was the [[Indian National Congress]] nominee on the [[Radcliffe Line|Radcliffe Commission]] that defined the boundaries of India and [[Pakistan]].\n\nJustice Mahajan made his name as an accomplished [[lawyer]], a respected [[judge]], and an influential [[politician]]. As a judge he was incisive and forthright and had many leading judgments to his credit.\n\n== Early life ==\nMehr Chand Mahajan was born in [[Nagrota]] in the [[Kangra district]] of Punjab, [[British India]] in 1889. His father, Lala Brij Lal, was an advocate, who later established a reputed legal practice at [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharmsala]].<ref name=Rohmetra>Ravi Rohmetra, [http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/mehr-chand-mahajan-pm-jk/ Mehr Chand Mahajan as PM of J&K], Daily Excelsior, 23 December 2016.</ref>\n\nAfter completing middle school, Mahajan went to study in the [[Government College, Lahore]], graduating in 1910. He enrolled in M.Sc. Chemistry, but switched to law following persuasion from his father. He earned an LL.B. degree in 1912.<ref name=Rohmetra/>\n\n== Career as a lawyer ==\nMahajan started his career as a lawyer in 1913 in Dharamsala, where he spent a year practising. He spent the next four years (1914-1918) as a lawyer in [[Gurdaspur]]. He then practiced law in [[Lahore]] from 1918 to 1943. During his time there, he served as president of the High Court Bar Association of Lahore (1938 to 1943).\n\n==Dewan of Jammu and Kashmir==\nMahajan was Dewan of [[Jammu and Kashmir]] state during 1947 and played a role in the accession of the state to India.but the first prime of jammu kashmir was sheikh abdullah with elected from peoples when 1st time election held in kashmir <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/opinion/what-soured-the-promise-of-kashmir/cid/1686431|title=What soured the promise of Kashmir|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-18}}</ref>\n\n== Chief Justice, Supreme Court of India ==\nMahajan took office as the third [[Chief Justice of India]] on 4 January 1954. He was the head of India's judicial system for almost a year, until his retirement on 22 December 1954 (mandatory retirement at age 65). Before becoming Chief Justice he served as one of the first Judges of the Supreme Court of independent India from 4 October 1948 to 3 January 1954.\n\n== Other positions of note ==\n* Director, [[Punjab National Bank]], 1933\u201343\n* Pres. D.A.V. College, Managing Committee, 1938\u201343\n* Fellow and Syndic, [[University of the Punjab|Punjab University]], 1940\u201347\n* Judge, [[Lahore High Court]], 1943\n* All India Fruit Products Association Bombay Session, 1945\n* Member, R.I.N. Mutiny Commission, 1946\n* 1947 Dewan, [[Jammu and Kashmir]] State 1947-48\n* Judge, East [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]] High Court\n* Punjab Boundary Commission, 1947\n* Syndic, East Punjab University, 1947\u201350\n* Constitutional Adviser to His Highness the Maharaja of [[Bikaner]], 1948\n* Hon. Degree of LL.D., Punjab University; 1948\n* Member, Fruit Development Board, Punjab\n* Commission on Belgaum (dispute between Karnataka and Maharashtra), 1967\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in/judges/bio/mcmahajan.htm Mehr Chand Mahajan]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Janak Singh]]\n| title  = [[Prime Minister of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| years  = 1947\u20131948\n| after  = [[Sheikh Abdullah]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-legal}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chief Justice of India]] | before=[[M. Patanjali Sastri]] | after=[[Bijan Kumar Mukherjea]] | years=3 January 1954 \u2013 22 December 1954}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chief Justices of India}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahajan, Mehr Chand}}\n[[Category:History of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of India]]\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kangra, Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:People of the 1947 Kashmir conflict]]\n\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Justice Mehr Chand Mahajan\n| office              = Chief Justice of India\n| order               = 3rd\n| honorific-prefix    = The Honourable\n| honorific-suffix    = \n| image               = Justice_Mehr_Chand_Mahajan.jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| appointer           = [[Rajendra Prasad]]\n| predecessor         = [[M. Patanjali Sastri]]\n| successor           = [[Bijan Kumar Mukherjea]]\n| birth_place         = [[Kangra district|Kangra]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[British Raj|British India]]<br><small>(now in [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[India]])</small>\n| death_date          = 1967\n| website             = http://www.mehrchandmahajan.org\n| term_start          = 4 January 1954\n| term_end            = 22 December 1954\n| term_start2         = 15 October 1947\n| term_end2           = 5 March 1948\n| Son                 = Vikram Mahajan\n}}\n\n'''Justice Mehr Chand Mahajan''' (23 December 1889 in [[Nagrota]], [[Kangra district]] \u2013 1967) was the third Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of India]]. Prior to that he was the [[Dewan]] of [[Jammu and Kashmir]] during the reign of Maharaja [[Hari Singh]] and played a key role in the accession of J&K to [[India]]. He was the [[Indian National Congress]] nominee on the [[Radcliffe Line|Radcliffe Commission]] that defined the boundaries of India and [[Pakistan]].\n\nJustice Mahajan made his name as an accomplished [[lawyer]], a respected [[judge]], and an influential [[politician]]. As a judge he was incisive and forthright and had many leading judgments to his credit.\n\n== Early life ==\nMehr Chand Mahajan was born in [[Nagrota]] in the [[Kangra district]] of Punjab, [[British India]] in 1889. His father, Lala Brij Lal, was an advocate, who later established a reputed legal practice at [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharmsala]].<ref name=Rohmetra>Ravi Rohmetra, [http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/mehr-chand-mahajan-pm-jk/ Mehr Chand Mahajan as PM of J&K], Daily Excelsior, 23 December 2016.</ref>\n\nAfter completing middle school, Mahajan went to study in the [[Government College, Lahore]], graduating in 1910. He enrolled in M.Sc. Chemistry, but switched to law following persuasion from his father. He earned an LL.B. degree in 1912.<ref name=Rohmetra/>\n\n== Career as a lawyer ==\nMahajan started his career as a lawyer in 1913 in Dharamsala, where he spent a year practising. He spent the next four years (1914-1918) as a lawyer in [[Gurdaspur]]. He then practiced law in [[Lahore]] from 1918 to 1943. During his time there, he served as president of the High Court Bar Association of Lahore (1938 to 1943).\n\n==Dewan of Jammu and Kashmir==\nMahajan was Dewan of [[Jammu and Kashmir]] state during 1947 and played a role in the accession of the state to India.but the first prime of jammu kashmir was sheikh abdullah with elected from peoples when 1st time election held in kashmir <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/opinion/what-soured-the-promise-of-kashmir/cid/1686431|title=What soured the promise of Kashmir|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-18}}</ref>\n\n== Chief Justice, Supreme Court of India ==\nMahajan took office as the third [[Chief Justice of India]] on 4 January 1954. He was the head of India's judicial system for almost a year, until his retirement on 22 December 1954 (mandatory retirement at age 65). Before becoming Chief Justice he served as one of the first Judges of the Supreme Court of independent India from 4 October 1948 to 3 January 1954.\n\n== Other positions of note ==\n* Director, [[Punjab National Bank]], 1933\u201343\n* Pres. D.A.V. College, Managing Committee, 1938\u201343\n* Fellow and Syndic, [[University of the Punjab|Punjab University]], 1940\u201347\n* Judge, [[Lahore High Court]], 1943\n* All India Fruit Products Association Bombay Session, 1945\n* Member, R.I.N. Mutiny Commission, 1946\n* 1947 Dewan , [[Jammu and Kashmir]] State 1947-48\n* Judge, East [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]] High Court\n* Punjab Boundary Commission, 1947\n* Syndic, East Punjab University, 1947\u201350\n* Constitutional Adviser to His Highness the Maharaja of [[Bikaner]], 1948\n* Hon. Degree of LL.D., Punjab University; 1948\n* Member, Fruit Development Board, Punjab\n* Commission on Belgaum (dispute between Karnataka and Maharashtra), 1967\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in/judges/bio/mcmahajan.htm Mehr Chand Mahajan]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Janak Singh]]\n| title  = [[Prime Minister of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| years  = 1947\u20131948\n| after  = [[Sheikh Abdullah]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-legal}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chief Justice of India]] | before=[[M. Patanjali Sastri]] | after=[[Bijan Kumar Mukherjea]] | years=3 January 1954 \u2013 22 December 1954}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chief Justices of India}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahajan, Mehr Chand}}\n[[Category:History of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of India]]\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kangra, Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:People of the 1947 Kashmir conflict]]\n\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther positions of note:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mehr_Chand_Mahajan"}
{"title_page": "James Wysong", "text_new": "'''James Wysong''' is an American author who worked as a [[flight attendant]] with for a major air carrier for almost 18 years, and wrote about air travel under the pen name '''A. Frank Steward'''.<ref name=\"ClarkReview\"/><ref name=\"KeelerReview\"/>  He is a travel columnist for [[MSNBC]].<ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news |title=James Wysong, travel columnist |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/10913368/ns/travel/t/james-wysong/#.W-HwdidRfUI |accessdate=6 November 2018 |publisher=MSNBC}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New York Times]] described Wysong's pen name as \"wryly chosen.\"<ref name=\"ElliottGround\">{{cite news |last1=Elliott |first1=Chris |title=Looking for Friendly Skies? Stay on the Ground |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/23/business/looking-for-friendly-skies-stay-on-the-ground.html |accessdate=6 November 2018 |work=New York Times |date=23 August 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWysong was raised in [[Ojai, California]], the youngest of three children. In 1984 he joined the Army as a trumpet player based in Germany. The band toured Europe, \u201cplaying everything from nightclubs to opening ceremonies, but 75% of our performances were at German beer festivals.\u201d{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIn 1987 he left the military and went to college in California. Fluent in the German language, Wysong joined [[Pan American Airlines]] in 1989. He was based in London, England, where he met his wife, Antonia, who is also employed by the airlines, starting as a flight attendant and later as a pilot. Wysong completed his degree in computer science from [[Thames Valley University]] in England. After Pan Am went out of business, he went to work for the airline that took over Pan Am's flying routes, and eventually moved back the East Coast of the United States in 1999. He and Antonia had a baby boy named Oliver James Wysong on February 2, 2006.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Writing career==\nWysong aka A. Frank Steward continues to fly and write about his experiences in-flight. He has a weekly column at Tripso.com and [MSNBC.com]. He has flown over 6 million miles, encountered over half a million passengers, endured over 1,000 different delays and cancellations, argued with over 500 frequent flyers, and has flown to approximately 100 countries.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nHis hobbies include [[people watching]], traveling, writing, chess, running, and lucid dreaming. He has completed a novel and a screenplay about a young man's adventures through lucid dreaming titled ''Dream Weaver'', and is currently writing another novel/screenplay titled ''Shady Acres''.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nAuthors who influenced him in his budding writing career include [[Jack London]] and [[Robert Fulghum]], who taught him that \u201cyou have to live life in order to write about life.\u201d His favorite quote is from Jack London: \u201cI would rather be a superb meteor, every atom of me in magnificent glow, than a sleepy and permanent planet. The proper function of man is to live, not to exist. I shall not waste my days in trying to prolong them. I shall use my time.\u201d{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nAccording to [[USA Today]] and [[The Globe and Mail]], Wysong's first book, ''The Air Traveler's Survival Guide,'' was not widely reviewed because it was published in September 2001 when news media focused on the 9/11 attacks to the exclusion of other types of coverage.<ref name=\"ClarkReview\"/><ref name=\"McArthurReview\">{{cite news |last1=McArthur |first1=Douglas |title=Will that be chicken, beef or possum? (book review) |publisher=Globe and Mail |date=30 January 2002|id={{ProQuest|384254512}} }}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* ''The Air Traveler's Survival Guide'' (2001) ({{ISBN|1-57023-242-3}})<ref name=\"McArthurReview\"/><ref name=\"Globetrotting\">{{cite news |title=Globetrotting (book review) |publisher=[[The Times-Picayune]] |date=23 December 2001|id={{ProQuest|415438374}} }}</ref>\n* ''The Plane Truth: Shift Happens at 35,000 Feet'' (2003) ({{ISBN|1-57023-211-3}})<ref name=\"ClarkReview\">{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Jayne |title=A frank steward reveals 'Plane Truth' (book review) |publisher=USA Today |date=7 November 2003|id={{ProQuest|408892528}} }}</ref><ref name=\"HanlonReview\">{{cite news |last1=Hanlon |first1=Michael |title=Book reveals the plane truth (book review) |publisher=[[Toronto Star]] |date=16 February 2002|id={{ProQuest|438401148}} }}</ref>\n* ''Air Travel Tales from the Flight Crew'' (2005)<ref name=\"KeelerReview\">{{cite news |last1=Keeler |first1=Janet |title=Tales from above Series: SIDE TRIP (book review) |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |date=1 December 2005|id={{ProQuest|264054912}} }}</ref><ref name=\"JetLag\">{{cite news |title=Advice on air travel, from germs to jet lag (book review) |publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]] |date=10 December 2005|id={{ProQuest|242223055}} }}</ref> ({{ISBN|1-57023-242-3}})<ref name=\"FlightCrew\">{{cite news |title=Air Travel Tales From the Flight Crew |url=https://www.chron.com/life/travel/article/Air-Travel-Tales-From-the-Flight-Crew-1634687.php |accessdate=6 November 2018 |agency=AP |publisher=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=22 January 2006}}</ref>\n* ''More Air Travel Tips and Tales From the Flight Crew'' (2008)<ref name=\"FlyingHigh\">{{cite news |title=Gear guides: 'Flying High With A Frank Steward |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2008/03/15/gear-guides-flying-high-with-a-frank-steward/ |accessdate=6 November 2018 |publisher=[[The Mercury News]] |date=15 March 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"BrownReview\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=J.D. |title=Flying High With A Frank Steward (brief book review) |agency=McClatchy - Tribune News Service |date=10 March 2008|id={{ProQuest|456848351}} }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tripso.com/columnists/wysong/ Column archive at Tripso.com]\n* [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/10913368 MSNBC bio]\n* [