{"title_page": "Big Bang (financial markets)", "text_new": "{{other uses of|Big Bang}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n[[File:Bishopsgate2.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Bishopsgate]] in [[London]]]]\n\nThe phrase '''Big Bang''', used in reference to the sudden [[deregulation]] of [[financial market]]s, was coined to describe measures, including abolition of fixed commission charges and of the distinction between [[stockjobber]]s and [[stockbrokers]] on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and change from [[Open outcry|open-outcry]] to [[electronic trading|electronic, screen-based trading]], effected by [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] in 1986.\n\n==History==\nThe Big Bang was the result of an agreement in 1983 by the Thatcher government and the London Stock Exchange to settle a wide-ranging antitrust case that had been initiated during the previous government by the [[Office of Fair Trading]] against the London Stock Exchange under the [[Restrictive Trade Practices Act 1956]]. These restrictive practices included the London Stock Exchange's rules establishing fixed minimum commissions, the \"single capacity\" rule (which enforced a separation between brokers acting as agents for their clients on commission and jobbers who made the markets and theoretically provided liquidity by holding lines of stocks and shares on their books), the requirement that both brokers and jobbers should be independent and not part of any wider financial group, and the stock exchange's exclusion of all foreigners from stock exchange membership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cps.org.uk/files/reports/original/111028101637-20061019EconomyBigBang20YearsOn.pdf |publisher=Centre for Policy Studies |accessdate=14 June 2015 |date=October 2006 |title=Big Bang 20 years on}}</ref>\n\nThe day the London Stock Exchange's rules changed on 27 October 1986 was dubbed the \"Big Bang\" because of the increase in market activity expected from an aggregation of measures designed to alter the structure of the [[financial market]].\n\nThe effect of the Big Bang led to significant changes to the structure of the financial markets in London. The changes saw many of the old firms being taken over by large banks both foreign and domestic and would lead in the following years to further changes to the [[financial regulation|regulatory environment]] that would eventually lead to the creation of the [[Financial Services Authority]].<ref>{{cite news  | title = In Depth \u2013 Big Bang | work = [[Financial Times]] | date= 29 October 2006 | url = http://www.ft.com/indepth/bigbang | accessdate = 29 October 2006 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061115010307/http://www.ft.com/indepth/bigbang| archivedate= 15 November 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Consequences==\nThe effects of Big Bang were dramatic, with London's place as a financial capital decisively strengthened, to the point where it is arguably the world's most important financial centre.<ref name=20061026independent>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/the-day-big-bang-blasted-the-old-boys-into-oblivion-422005.html |title=The day Big Bang blasted the old boys into oblivion |work=[[The Independent]] |date=26 October 2006 |first=Danny |last=Fortson}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Treanor | first = Jill  | title = Revolution hailed but City warned of a looming fight for supremacy | work = [[The Guardian]] |date= 27 October 2006  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/business/2006/oct/27/politics.economicpolicy| accessdate = 29 October 2006 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061104075645/http://business.guardian.co.uk/story/0%2C%2C1932560%2C00.html| archivedate= 4 November 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref> The [[Lawson Boom|boom]] resulted in the relocation of institutions into new developments in the nearby [[Isle of Dogs]] area, particularly that of [[Canary Wharf]].\n\nAlthough the \"Big Bang\" eased stock market transactions there is a debate in the UK about how far it affected the [[2007\u20132012 global financial crisis]]. In 2010, [[Nigel Lawson]], Thatcher's [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] at the time of the Big Bang, appeared on the radio programme ''[[Analysis (radio programme)|Analysis]]'' to discuss the banking reform. He explained that the [[2007\u20132012 global financial crisis]] was an unintended consequence of the \"Big Bang\".<ref name=analysis>{{cite episode|series=Analysis|title=A price worth paying?|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio/player/b00qbxwj|minutes=0\u201313|date=1 February 2010|network=BBC Radio 4|accessdate=12 August 2012}}</ref> He said that UK investment banks were previously very cautious, as they operated with their own money, but after merging with major retail banks, the depositors' savings were put at risk, and according to the programme this led U.S. banks to follow suit.<ref name=analysis/>\n\nIn 2011 former British Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] expressed regret at not implementing tougher regulations during his tenure of chancellor between 1997 and 2007, responding to \"relentless pressure\" from the City not to over-regulate.\n\n{{cquote|We know in retrospect what we missed. We set up the Financial Services Authority (FSA) believing that the problem would come from the failure of an individual institution, so we created a monitoring system which was looking at individual institutions. That was the big mistake. \n\nWe didn't understand how risk was spread across the system, we didn't understand the entanglements of different institutions with the other and we didn't understand even though we talked about it just how global things were, including a shadow banking system as well as a banking system.\n\nThat was our mistake, but I'm afraid it was a mistake made by just about everybody who was in the regulatory business.|source=Gordon Brown<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-13032013|title=Brown admits 'mistake' on banks|date=2011-04-11|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref>}}\n\n==Similar events ==\nSubsequent similar actions, such as the deregulation of the Japanese financial markets circa 1997, have analogously also been tagged with the phrase Big Bang.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Katayama, Osamu|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020612044547/http://www.lookjapan.com/LBcoverstory/97NovCS.htm|title=JAPAN'S BIG BANG|magazine=[[Look Japan]]|date=November 1997|accessdate=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[The Wimbledon Effect]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Economy of the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:1986 in economics]]\n[[Category:1986 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Economy of London]]\n[[Category:Economic liberalization]]\n[[Category:Economics of regulation]]\n[[Category:Financial markets]]\n[[Category:London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Separation of investment and retail banking]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses of|Big Bang}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n[[Image:Bishopsgate2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bishopsgate]] in [[London]]]]\nThe phrase '''Big Bang''', used in reference to the sudden [[deregulation]] of [[financial market]]s, was coined to describe measures, including abolition of fixed commission charges and of the distinction between [[stockjobber]]s and [[stockbrokers]] on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and change from [[Open outcry|open-outcry]] to [[electronic trading|electronic, screen-based trading]], effected by [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] in 1986.\n\n==History==\nThe Big Bang was the result of an agreement in 1983 by the Thatcher government and the London Stock Exchange to settle a wide-ranging antitrust case that had been initiated during the previous government by the [[Office of Fair Trading]] against the London Stock Exchange under the [[Restrictive Trade Practices Act 1956]]. These restrictive practices included the London Stock Exchange's rules establishing fixed minimum commissions, the \"single capacity\" rule (which enforced a separation between brokers acting as agents for their clients on commission and jobbers who made the markets and theoretically provided liquidity by holding lines of stocks and shares on their books), the requirement that both brokers and jobbers should be independent and not part of any wider financial group, and the stock exchange's exclusion of all foreigners from stock exchange membership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cps.org.uk/files/reports/original/111028101637-20061019EconomyBigBang20YearsOn.pdf |publisher=Centre for Policy Studies |accessdate=14 June 2015 |date=October 2006 |title=Big Bang 20 years on}}</ref>\n\nThe day the London Stock Exchange's rules changed on 27 October 1986 was dubbed the \"Big Bang\" because of the increase in market activity expected from an aggregation of measures designed to alter the structure of the [[financial market]].\n\nThe effect of the Big Bang led to significant changes to the structure of the financial markets in London. The changes saw many of the old firms being taken over by large banks both foreign and domestic and would lead in the following years to further changes to the [[financial regulation|regulatory environment]] that would eventually lead to the creation of the [[Financial Services Authority]].<ref>{{cite news  | title = In Depth \u2013 Big Bang | work = [[Financial Times]] | date= 29 October 2006 | url = http://www.ft.com/indepth/bigbang | accessdate = 29 October 2006 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061115010307/http://www.ft.com/indepth/bigbang| archivedate= 15 November 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Consequences==\nThe effects of Big Bang were dramatic, with London's place as a financial capital decisively strengthened, to the point where it is arguably the world's most important financial centre.<ref name=20061026independent>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/the-day-big-bang-blasted-the-old-boys-into-oblivion-422005.html |title=The day Big Bang blasted the old boys into oblivion |work=[[The Independent]] |date=26 October 2006 |first=Danny |last=Fortson}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Treanor | first = Jill  | title = Revolution hailed but City warned of a looming fight for supremacy | work = [[The Guardian]] |date= 27 October 2006  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/business/2006/oct/27/politics.economicpolicy| accessdate = 29 October 2006 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061104075645/http://business.guardian.co.uk/story/0%2C%2C1932560%2C00.html| archivedate= 4 November 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref> The [[Lawson Boom|boom]] resulted in the relocation of institutions into new developments in the nearby [[Isle of Dogs]] area, particularly that of [[Canary Wharf]].\n\nAlthough the \"Big Bang\" eased stock market transactions there is a debate in the UK about how far it affected the [[2007\u20132012 global financial crisis]]. In 2010, [[Nigel Lawson]], Thatcher's [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] at the time of the Big Bang, appeared on the radio programme ''[[Analysis (radio programme)|Analysis]]'' to discuss the banking reform. He explained that the [[2007\u20132012 global financial crisis]] was an unintended consequence of the \"Big Bang\".<ref name=analysis>{{cite episode|series=Analysis|title=A price worth paying?|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio/player/b00qbxwj|minutes=0\u201313|date=1 February 2010|network=BBC Radio 4|accessdate=12 August 2012}}</ref> He said that UK investment banks were previously very cautious, as they operated with their own money, but after merging with major retail banks, the depositors' savings were put at risk, and according to the programme this led U.S. banks to follow suit.<ref name=analysis/>\n\nIn 2011 former British Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] expressed regret at not implementing tougher regulations during his tenure of chancellor between 1997 and 2007, responding to \"relentless pressure\" from the City not to over-regulate.\n\n{{cquote|We know in retrospect what we missed. We set up the Financial Services Authority (FSA) believing that the problem would come from the failure of an individual institution, so we created a monitoring system which was looking at individual institutions. That was the big mistake. \n\nWe didn't understand how risk was spread across the system, we didn't understand the entanglements of different institutions with the other and we didn't understand even though we talked about it just how global things were, including a shadow banking system as well as a banking system.\n\nThat was our mistake, but I'm afraid it was a mistake made by just about everybody who was in the regulatory business.|source=Gordon Brown<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-13032013|title=Brown admits 'mistake' on banks|date=2011-04-11|access-date=2019-06-22|language=en-GB}}</ref>}}\n\n==Similar events ==\nSubsequent similar actions, such as the deregulation of the Japanese financial markets circa 1997, have analogously also been tagged with the phrase Big Bang.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Katayama, Osamu|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020612044547/http://www.lookjapan.com/LBcoverstory/97NovCS.htm|title=JAPAN'S BIG BANG|magazine=[[Look Japan]]|date=November 1997|accessdate=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Wimbledon Effect]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Economy of the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:1986 in economics]]\n[[Category:1986 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Economy of London]]\n[[Category:Economic liberalization]]\n[[Category:Economics of regulation]]\n[[Category:Financial markets]]\n[[Category:London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Separation of investment and retail banking]]\n", "name_user": "Voidxor", "label": "safe", "comment": "The language parameter is only necessary for non-English sources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Bang_(financial_markets)"}
{"title_page": "Jorge Paulo Lemann", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jorge Paulo Lemann\n| image              = Jorge Paulo Lemann em fevereiro de 2012.png\n| birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|August 26, 1939}}\n| birth_place        = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n| residence          = [[Rapperswil-Jona]], Switzerland and Sao Paulo\n| citizenship        = Brazil <br> Switzerland<ref name=HZ>Stefan Barmettler: ''Der Brauer vom Zuerichsee.'' Handelszeitung, Nr. 19, May 8, 2014, p. 7</ref>\n| education          = [[Harvard University]]<ref name=\"forbes.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/jorge-paulo-lemann/|title=The World's Billionaires | work=Forbes}}</ref>\n| networth           = US$24.6 billion (October 2019)<ref name=\"Bloomberg.com\"/>\n| spouse             = Married<ref name=\"forbes.com\"/>\n| children           = 6<ref name=\"forbes.com\"/>\n}}\n\n'''Jorge Paulo Lemann''' (born August 26, 1939)<ref name=\"bloomberg list\">{{cite web|title=Today's ranking of the world's richest people of brazil|url=http://topics.bloomberg.com/bloomberg-billionaires-index/|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=30 November 2012|date=29 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214085457/http://topics.bloomberg.com/bloomberg-billionaires-index/|archivedate=14 December 2012}}</ref> is a Brazilian businessman, and investment banker with dual [[Brazil]]ian and [[Swiss]] citizenship.<ref>[https://www.munzinger.de/search/go/document.jsp?id=00000029524 ''Jorge Paulo Lemann.''] Internationales Biographisches Archiv 24/2018 vom 12. Juni 2018. Retrieved 12 April 2020.</ref>  As of October 2019, Lemann was ranked as the 37th richest person in the world by [[Forbes]], with an estimated [[net worth]] of {{US$| 24.6 billion|link=https://origin.www.bloomberg.com/billionaires/profiles/jorge-p-lemann/}}.<ref name=\"forbes.com\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nIn 1939, Lemann was born in [[Rio de Janeiro]] to Paul Lemann,<ref name=\"HZ\"/> a Swiss immigrant who founded the dairy manufacturer, Leco, and Anna Yvette Truebner, a Brazilian of Swiss origin.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.jusbrasil.com.br/diarios/2943242/pg-96-secao-1-diario-oficial-da-uniao-dou-de-20-08-1959 |title=DOU 20/08/1959 - Pg. 96 - Se\u00e7\u00e3o 1 &#124; Di\u00e1rio Oficial da Uni\u00e3o &#124; Di\u00e1rios JusBrasil |publisher=Jusbrasil.com.br |date= |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1246&dat=19660701&id=GeIRAAAAIBAJ&pg=1658,119970&hl=pt-PT |title=Jornal do Brasil - Pesquisa no arquivo do Google Not\u00edcias |date=1966-07-01 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docslide.us/documents/abi-lemann-telles-article.html |title=ABI Lemann Telles Article - Documents |publisher=Docslide.us |date=2015-04-08 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> Lemann attended the [[American School of Rio de Janeiro]].<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/articles/2013-08-29/the-brazilian-billionaire-who-controls-your-beer-your-condiments-and-your-whopper#p2 | work=Bloomberg | title=Jorge Lemann: He Is ... the World's Most Interesting Billionaire}}</ref>\n\nHis father died in a bus accident in 1953, when Lemann was 14.<ref name=\"infomoney1\">{{cite web |author=Jo\u00e3o Sandrini |url=http://www.infomoney.com.br/negocios/noticia/2734075/fatos-que-voce-provavelmente-desconhece-sobre-homem-mais-rico-brasil |title=17 fatos que voc\u00ea (provavelmente) desconhece sobre o homem mais rico do Brasil |publisher=InfoMoney |date=2013-04-16 |accessdate=2015-09-26 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150420093845/http://www.infomoney.com.br/negocios/noticia/2734075/fatos-que-voce-provavelmente-desconhece-sobre-homem-mais-rico-brasil |archive-date=2015-04-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1961, he received a bachelor's degree in economics from [[Harvard University]]. According to Lemann's own admission, he did not enjoy his time at Harvard, stating that \"My first year at Harvard was horrible. I was only 17 and I missed the beach and the sun a lot. Boston was too cold for me. It was my first time in the USA and I was not used to study or to write; we have to write a lot in Harvard. My grades were the worst possible.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ricardogeromel/2013/03/15/from-harvard-slacker-to-wimbledon-to-buffetts-professor-and-partner-meet-lemann-brazils-richest/#cd868ab74ed9|title=From Harvard Slacker To Wimbledon To Buffett's Professor And Partner: Meet Lemann, Brazil's Richest|last=Geromel|first=Ricardo|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ricardogeromel/2013/03/15/from-harvard-slacker-to-wimbledon-to-buffetts-professor-and-partner-meet-lemann-brazils-richest/|title=From Harvard Slacker To Wimbledon To Buffett's Professor And Partner: Meet Lemann, Brazil's Richest|last=Geromel|first=Ricardo|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref> After setting off fireworks on the last day of his freshman year, he was reprimanded and considered dropping out, but ultimately decided to stay on.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ad85be00-d2ff-11e4-b7a8-00144feab7de|title=Jorge Paulo Lemann, a lean, hungry mogul|last=|first=|date=|website=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLemann always wanted to become an inventor. As a kid he admired [[Thomas Edison]]. He built different machines but they usually did not work out. Lemann was also an avid tennis amateur. He won the Brazilian national tennis championship five times.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\" /><ref name=\"bornrich.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bornrich.com/jorge-paulo-lemann.html |title=Jorge Paulo Lemann Net Worth - biography, quotes, wiki, assets, cars, homes and more |publisher=Bornrich.com |date= March 2012|accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> He participated in the [[Davis Cup]] twice, once as part of the Swiss Davis Cup team and once on behalf of the Brazilian team,<ref name=\"HZ\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=10003881|title=Jorge Paulo LEMANN|publisher=Daviscup.com|accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> and also played at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] in 1962.<ref>{{cite web |title=Player archive \u2013 Jorge Paulo Lemann |url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/draws_archive/player_profile/9260dd4a-c998-4c69-8a51-3035442977d8.html |website=Wimbledon |publisher=[[AELTC]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1961 to 1962, he worked as a trainee at [[Credit Suisse]] in Geneva.<ref name=HZ /> In 1966, the first company in which Lemann had equity interest, a lending company called Invesco, went bankrupt. Lemann had a 2% equity stake.<ref name=\"infomoney1\"/> In 1971, Lemann, [[Carlos Alberto Sicupira]] and [[Marcel Herrmann Telles]] founded the Brazilian [[investment banking]] firm [[Banco Garantia]]. Undaunted by a market crash that came only weeks later, Lemann was eventually able to build Garantia into one of the country's most prestigious and innovative investment banks, described in [[Forbes]] as \"a Brazilian version of [[Goldman Sachs]].\"<ref name=\"alumni.hbs.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=1990 |title=Jorge Paulo Lemann, A.B. 1961; Carlos A. Sicupira, OPM 9, 1984; Marcel H. Telles, OPM 10, 1985 - Alumni - Harvard Business School |publisher=Alumni.hbs.edu |date=2009-01-01 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ascarelli |first=Silvia |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/6-things-to-know-about-kraft-foods-buyer-3g-2015-03-25?siteid=rss&rss=1 |title=6 things to know about Kraft Foods buyer 3G |publisher=MarketWatch |date=2015-03-25 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> Lemann and his partners now help to control AB Inbev as members of its board of directors.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nIn 1994, he suffered a heart attack, at age 54.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/articles/2013-08-29/the-brazilian-billionaire-who-controls-your-beer-your-condiments-and-your-whopper#p4 | work=Bloomberg | title=Jorge Lemann: He Is ... the World's Most Interesting Billionaire}}</ref> Following the Asian financial crisis, Banco Garantia was sold to [[Credit Suisse First Boston]] in July 1998 for $675m.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"bornrich.com\"/><ref name=\"alumni.hbs.edu\"/>\n\nFrom 1990 to 2001, he served as a member of the board of directors of [[Brahma (beer)|Companhia Cervejaria Brahma]].<ref>Inbev Prospectus January 2005</ref> \nLemann is a director of [[Endeavor (non-profit)|Endeavor]]'s Brazil office. Endeavor is an international non-profit development organization that finds and supports high-impact entrepreneurs in emerging markets. Later he and his partners, who founded private equity company ''[[GP Investments|GP Investimentos]]'',<ref name=HZ /> bought control of two Brazilian breweries ([[Brahma beer]] and [[Companhia Antarctica Paulista]]) that became [[AmBev]]. In 2003 AmBev had a pretax [[profit margin]] of 35 percent on sales of US$2.7 billion. By 2004, it controlled 65 percent of the Brazilian beer market and almost 80 percent of Argentina's, with monopoly positions in [[Paraguay]], [[Uruguay]], and [[Bolivia]].<ref>Richard Tomlison, ''The New King of Beer'', Fortune Magazine, October 18, 2004</ref>\n\nAmBev merged with [[Interbrew]] of Belgium in August 2004. The stock of the combined firm, [[InBev]], rose 40 percent during 2005. InBev then announced it would buy the American brewer Anheuser-Busch in 2008 for $46 billion in a highly controversial deal, making it the world's largest brewer, [[Anheuser-Busch Inbev]] (abbreviated as '''AB Inbev''') securing Lemann's status as one of the new \"Kings\" of beer.<ref>Julie MacIntosh, Dethroning the King: The Hostile Takeover of Anheuser-Busch, an American Icon; 2010</ref>\n\nLemann is a board member of [[Lojas Americanas]] S.A. and was a former board member of [[Gillette (brand)|Gillette]] (where he first worked with [[Warren Buffett]]); chairman of the Latin American Advisory Committee of the [[New York Stock Exchange]]; founder and board member of Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Estudar, which provides scholarships for Brazilian students; and a member of the international advisory board of [[DaimlerChrysler]].\n\nLemann is a co-founder of Brazilian investment firm [[3G Capital]], which owns brands such as Burger King, Anheuser-Busch and Heinz.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/10/business/dealbook/warren-buffett-jorge-paulo-lemann-brazil-conference.html|title=When Warren Met Jorge Paulo: Buffett and Lemann Recall Their First Deal|last=Sreeharsha|first=Vinod|date=2017-04-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  In September 2010, 3G launched a $4 billion bid, at a 45% premium over market, for all the stock of [[Burger King]]. \"3G was advised in the BK offer by [[Lazard]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], [[Barclays Capital]] and the law firm [[Kirkland & Ellis]]. 3G already has some experience in burgers and fries, having previously invested in [[Wendy's]].\"<ref>[http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/09/02/burger-king-to-sell-itself-to-3g-for-4-billion/?hp \"Burger King to Sell Itself to 3G for $4 Billion\"], \"Dealbook\" blog, ''The New York Times'', September 2, 2010, 9:50 am. Retrieved 2010-09-02.</ref> Together with [[Berkshire Hathaway]], 3G Capital acquired the [[H. J. Heinz Company]] for $28 billion in 2013. Its new CEO [[Bernardo Hees]] is a former manager of Burger King.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.heinz.com/press-release/finance/berkshire-hathaway-and-3g-capital-complete-acquisition-hj-heinz-company |title=Berkshire Hathaway and 3G Capital Complete Acquisition of H.J. Heinz Company &#124; Heinz Online Newsroom |publisher=News.heinz.com |date=2013-06-07 |accessdate=2015-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928223057/http://news.heinz.com/press-release/finance/berkshire-hathaway-and-3g-capital-complete-acquisition-hj-heinz-company |archive-date=2015-09-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The same group announced the merger of [[Kraft Foods]] with Heinz in March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-3QV6OO/4151635958x0x817718/bb5a3884-b3ad-4249-9fc6-5af812a1a437/Kraft_Heinz_News_Release_2015-03-25.pdf|title=Merger announcement Kraft with Heinz|date=March 2015|publisher=Files.shareholder.com|accessdate=2015-09-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402120544/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-3QV6OO/4151635958x0x817718/bb5a3884-b3ad-4249-9fc6-5af812a1a437/Kraft_Heinz_News_Release_2015-03-25.pdf|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLemann married twice and has six children, three with his first wife and three with his second wife Susanna.<ref name=\"EN\">Alexandre Teixeira and Camila Hessel: [http://epocanegocios.globo.com/Revista/Epocanegocios/0,,EDR82833-8374,00.html ''O legado de Lemann.''] In: ''[[Epoca Neg\u00f3cios]].'' English translation: [https://docslide.us/documents/abi-lemann-telles-article.html ''Lemann's Legacy.''] ''English Docslide'', 2015-04-08. Retrieved 2018-10-20.</ref>  He usually spends his time between [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Rapperswil SG|Rapperswil-Jona]] on [[Lake Zurich]],<ref name=\"HZ\" /> where his family lives, and [[St. Louis]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/jorge-paulo-lemann/ |title=Jorge Paulo Lemann |work=Forbes |date= |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzz.ch/aktuell/wirtschaft/wirtschaftsnachrichten/banker-braumeister-und-burgerketten-besitzer-1.17859828 |title=Multimilliard\u00e4r Jorge Paulo Lemann: Banker, Braumeister und Burgerketten-Besitzer - NZZ |publisher=Nzz.ch |date=2012-11-30 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> \n\nIn 1999, several gunmen attempted to kidnap his children on their way to school.<ref name=\":1\" /> The incident prompted Lemann to relocate permanently to Switzerland.<ref name=\":1\" /> According to a report,\" his children still attended school that day and Lemann was only a little late to the office.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.worldfinance.com/strategy/the-rise-and-rise-of-jorge-paulo-lemann|title=The rise and rise of Jorge Paulo Lemann|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nLemann rarely gives interviews or appears publicly, and is little known in the United States.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-08-29/jorge-lemann-he-is-dot-the-worlds-most-interesting-billionaire|title=Jorge Lemann: He Is ... the World's Most Interesting Billionaire|date=2013-08-30|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref> However, according to Bloomberg, in Brazil, Lemann is considered a \"business-class hero\", \"the wiry, white-haired conglomerateur who\u2019s part Buffett, part Sam Walton, part Roger Federer.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n<!-- <ref name=\"Billionaires 2010\">{{cite news\n  |title= The World's Billionaires (2011): #55 Jorge Paulo Lemann\n  |url= https://www.forbes.com/profile/jorge-paulo-lemann\n  |work= [[Forbes]] |date= March 3, 2010 |accessdate= February 24, 2011}}\n</ref> -->\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090916033210/http://www.latinbusinesschronicle.com/app/section.aspx?id=323 Latin America's most important businessmen]. ''Latin Business Chronicle''.\n* [http://latinvex.com/app/article.aspx?id=530&g=1 Brazil's Top 50 Businesspeople]. ''Latinvex''.\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Davis Cup player}}\n\n{{Anheuser-Busch InBev}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lemann, Jorge Paulo}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Rio de Janeiro (city)]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:Swiss people of Brazilian descent]]\n[[Category:Brazilian bankers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in brewing]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Swiss male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Brazilian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Swiss billionaires]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Anheuser\u2013Busch InBev people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jorge Paulo Lemann\n| image              = Jorge Paulo Lemann em fevereiro de 2012.png\n| birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|August 26, 1939}}\n| birth_place        = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n| residence          = [[Rapperswil-Jona]], Switzerland and Sao Paulo\n| citizenship        = Brazil <br> Switzerland<ref name=HZ>Stefan Barmettler: ''Der Brauer vom Zuerichsee.'' Handelszeitung, Nr. 19, May 8, 2014, p. 7</ref>\n| education          = [[Harvard University]]<ref name=\"forbes.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/jorge-paulo-lemann/|title=The World's Billionaires | work=Forbes}}</ref>\n| networth           = US$24.6 billion (October 2019)<ref name=\"Bloomberg.com\"/>\n| spouse             = Married<ref name=\"forbes.com\"/>\n| children           = 6<ref name=\"forbes.com\"/>\n}}\n\n'''Jorge Paulo Lemann''' (born August 26, 1939)<ref name=\"bloomberg list\">{{cite web|title=Today's ranking of the world's richest people of brazil|url=http://topics.bloomberg.com/bloomberg-billionaires-index/|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=30 November 2012|date=29 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214085457/http://topics.bloomberg.com/bloomberg-billionaires-index/|archivedate=14 December 2012}}</ref> is a Brazilian businessman with dual [[Brazil]]ian and [[Swiss]] citizenship.<ref>[https://www.munzinger.de/search/go/document.jsp?id=00000029524 ''Jorge Paulo Lemann.''] Internationales Biographisches Archiv 24/2018 vom 12. Juni 2018. Retrieved 12 April 2020.</ref>  As of October 2019, Lemann was ranked as the 37th richest person in the world by [[Forbes]], with an estimated [[net worth]] of {{US$| 24.6 billion|link=https://origin.www.bloomberg.com/billionaires/profiles/jorge-p-lemann/}}.<ref name=\"forbes.com\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nIn 1939, Lemann was born in [[Rio de Janeiro]] to Paul Lemann,<ref name=\"HZ\"/> a Swiss immigrant who founded the dairy manufacturer, Leco, and Anna Yvette Truebner, a Brazilian of Swiss origin.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.jusbrasil.com.br/diarios/2943242/pg-96-secao-1-diario-oficial-da-uniao-dou-de-20-08-1959 |title=DOU 20/08/1959 - Pg. 96 - Se\u00e7\u00e3o 1 &#124; Di\u00e1rio Oficial da Uni\u00e3o &#124; Di\u00e1rios JusBrasil |publisher=Jusbrasil.com.br |date= |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1246&dat=19660701&id=GeIRAAAAIBAJ&pg=1658,119970&hl=pt-PT |title=Jornal do Brasil - Pesquisa no arquivo do Google Not\u00edcias |date=1966-07-01 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docslide.us/documents/abi-lemann-telles-article.html |title=ABI Lemann Telles Article - Documents |publisher=Docslide.us |date=2015-04-08 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> Lemann attended the [[American School of Rio de Janeiro]].<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/articles/2013-08-29/the-brazilian-billionaire-who-controls-your-beer-your-condiments-and-your-whopper#p2 | work=Bloomberg | title=Jorge Lemann: He Is ... the World's Most Interesting Billionaire}}</ref>\n\nHis father died in a bus accident in 1953, when Lemann was 14.<ref name=\"infomoney1\">{{cite web |author=Jo\u00e3o Sandrini |url=http://www.infomoney.com.br/negocios/noticia/2734075/fatos-que-voce-provavelmente-desconhece-sobre-homem-mais-rico-brasil |title=17 fatos que voc\u00ea (provavelmente) desconhece sobre o homem mais rico do Brasil |publisher=InfoMoney |date=2013-04-16 |accessdate=2015-09-26 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150420093845/http://www.infomoney.com.br/negocios/noticia/2734075/fatos-que-voce-provavelmente-desconhece-sobre-homem-mais-rico-brasil |archive-date=2015-04-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1961, he received a bachelor's degree in economics from [[Harvard University]]. According to Lemann's own admission, he did not enjoy his time at Harvard, stating that \"My first year at Harvard was horrible. I was only 17 and I missed the beach and the sun a lot. Boston was too cold for me. It was my first time in the USA and I was not used to study or to write; we have to write a lot in Harvard. My grades were the worst possible.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ricardogeromel/2013/03/15/from-harvard-slacker-to-wimbledon-to-buffetts-professor-and-partner-meet-lemann-brazils-richest/#cd868ab74ed9|title=From Harvard Slacker To Wimbledon To Buffett's Professor And Partner: Meet Lemann, Brazil's Richest|last=Geromel|first=Ricardo|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ricardogeromel/2013/03/15/from-harvard-slacker-to-wimbledon-to-buffetts-professor-and-partner-meet-lemann-brazils-richest/|title=From Harvard Slacker To Wimbledon To Buffett's Professor And Partner: Meet Lemann, Brazil's Richest|last=Geromel|first=Ricardo|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref> After setting off fireworks on the last day of his freshman year, he was reprimanded and considered dropping out, but ultimately decided to stay on.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ad85be00-d2ff-11e4-b7a8-00144feab7de|title=Jorge Paulo Lemann, a lean, hungry mogul|last=|first=|date=|website=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLemann always wanted to become an inventor. As a kid he admired [[Thomas Edison]]. He built different machines but they usually did not work out. Lemann was also an avid tennis amateur. He won the Brazilian national tennis championship five times.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\" /><ref name=\"bornrich.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bornrich.com/jorge-paulo-lemann.html |title=Jorge Paulo Lemann Net Worth - biography, quotes, wiki, assets, cars, homes and more |publisher=Bornrich.com |date= March 2012|accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> He participated in the [[Davis Cup]] twice, once as part of the Swiss Davis Cup team and once on behalf of the Brazilian team,<ref name=\"HZ\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=10003881|title=Jorge Paulo LEMANN|publisher=Daviscup.com|accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> and also played at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] in 1962.<ref>{{cite web |title=Player archive \u2013 Jorge Paulo Lemann |url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/draws_archive/player_profile/9260dd4a-c998-4c69-8a51-3035442977d8.html |website=Wimbledon |publisher=[[AELTC]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1961 to 1962, he worked as a trainee at [[Credit Suisse]] in Geneva.<ref name=HZ /> In 1966, the first company in which Lemann had equity interest, a lending company called Invesco, went bankrupt. Lemann had a 2% equity stake.<ref name=\"infomoney1\"/> In 1971, Lemann, [[Carlos Alberto Sicupira]] and [[Marcel Herrmann Telles]] founded the Brazilian [[investment banking]] firm [[Banco Garantia]]. Undaunted by a market crash that came only weeks later, Lemann was eventually able to build Garantia into one of the country's most prestigious and innovative investment banks, described in [[Forbes]] as \"a Brazilian version of [[Goldman Sachs]].\"<ref name=\"alumni.hbs.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=1990 |title=Jorge Paulo Lemann, A.B. 1961; Carlos A. Sicupira, OPM 9, 1984; Marcel H. Telles, OPM 10, 1985 - Alumni - Harvard Business School |publisher=Alumni.hbs.edu |date=2009-01-01 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ascarelli |first=Silvia |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/6-things-to-know-about-kraft-foods-buyer-3g-2015-03-25?siteid=rss&rss=1 |title=6 things to know about Kraft Foods buyer 3G |publisher=MarketWatch |date=2015-03-25 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> Lemann and his partners now help to control AB Inbev as members of its board of directors.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nIn 1994, he suffered a heart attack, at age 54.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/articles/2013-08-29/the-brazilian-billionaire-who-controls-your-beer-your-condiments-and-your-whopper#p4 | work=Bloomberg | title=Jorge Lemann: He Is ... the World's Most Interesting Billionaire}}</ref> Following the Asian financial crisis, Banco Garantia was sold to [[Credit Suisse First Boston]] in July 1998 for $675m.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"bornrich.com\"/><ref name=\"alumni.hbs.edu\"/>\n\nFrom 1990 to 2001, he served as a member of the board of directors of [[Brahma (beer)|Companhia Cervejaria Brahma]].<ref>Inbev Prospectus January 2005</ref> \nLemann is a director of [[Endeavor (non-profit)|Endeavor]]'s Brazil office. Endeavor is an international non-profit development organization that finds and supports high-impact entrepreneurs in emerging markets. Later he and his partners, who founded private equity company ''[[GP Investments|GP Investimentos]]'',<ref name=HZ /> bought control of two Brazilian breweries ([[Brahma beer]] and [[Companhia Antarctica Paulista]]) that became [[AmBev]]. In 2003 AmBev had a pretax [[profit margin]] of 35 percent on sales of US$2.7 billion. By 2004, it controlled 65 percent of the Brazilian beer market and almost 80 percent of Argentina's, with monopoly positions in [[Paraguay]], [[Uruguay]], and [[Bolivia]].<ref>Richard Tomlison, ''The New King of Beer'', Fortune Magazine, October 18, 2004</ref>\n\nAmBev merged with [[Interbrew]] of Belgium in August 2004. The stock of the combined firm, [[InBev]], rose 40 percent during 2005. InBev then announced it would buy the American brewer Anheuser-Busch in 2008 for $46 billion in a highly controversial deal, making it the world's largest brewer, [[Anheuser-Busch Inbev]] (abbreviated as '''AB Inbev''') securing Lemann's status as one of the new \"Kings\" of beer.<ref>Julie MacIntosh, Dethroning the King: The Hostile Takeover of Anheuser-Busch, an American Icon; 2010</ref>\n\nLemann is a board member of [[Lojas Americanas]] S.A. and was a former board member of [[Gillette (brand)|Gillette]] (where he first worked with [[Warren Buffett]]); chairman of the Latin American Advisory Committee of the [[New York Stock Exchange]]; founder and board member of Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Estudar, which provides scholarships for Brazilian students; and a member of the international advisory board of [[DaimlerChrysler]].\n\nLemann is a co-founder of Brazilian investment firm [[3G Capital]], which owns brands such as Burger King, Anheuser-Busch and Heinz.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/10/business/dealbook/warren-buffett-jorge-paulo-lemann-brazil-conference.html|title=When Warren Met Jorge Paulo: Buffett and Lemann Recall Their First Deal|last=Sreeharsha|first=Vinod|date=2017-04-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  In September 2010, 3G launched a $4 billion bid, at a 45% premium over market, for all the stock of [[Burger King]]. \"3G was advised in the BK offer by [[Lazard]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], [[Barclays Capital]] and the law firm [[Kirkland & Ellis]]. 3G already has some experience in burgers and fries, having previously invested in [[Wendy's]].\"<ref>[http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/09/02/burger-king-to-sell-itself-to-3g-for-4-billion/?hp \"Burger King to Sell Itself to 3G for $4 Billion\"], \"Dealbook\" blog, ''The New York Times'', September 2, 2010, 9:50 am. Retrieved 2010-09-02.</ref> Together with [[Berkshire Hathaway]], 3G Capital acquired the [[H. J. Heinz Company]] for $28 billion in 2013. Its new CEO [[Bernardo Hees]] is a former manager of Burger King.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.heinz.com/press-release/finance/berkshire-hathaway-and-3g-capital-complete-acquisition-hj-heinz-company |title=Berkshire Hathaway and 3G Capital Complete Acquisition of H.J. Heinz Company &#124; Heinz Online Newsroom |publisher=News.heinz.com |date=2013-06-07 |accessdate=2015-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928223057/http://news.heinz.com/press-release/finance/berkshire-hathaway-and-3g-capital-complete-acquisition-hj-heinz-company |archive-date=2015-09-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The same group announced the merger of [[Kraft Foods]] with Heinz in March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-3QV6OO/4151635958x0x817718/bb5a3884-b3ad-4249-9fc6-5af812a1a437/Kraft_Heinz_News_Release_2015-03-25.pdf|title=Merger announcement Kraft with Heinz|date=March 2015|publisher=Files.shareholder.com|accessdate=2015-09-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402120544/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-3QV6OO/4151635958x0x817718/bb5a3884-b3ad-4249-9fc6-5af812a1a437/Kraft_Heinz_News_Release_2015-03-25.pdf|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLemann married twice and has six children, three with his first wife and three with his second wife Susanna.<ref name=\"EN\">Alexandre Teixeira and Camila Hessel: [http://epocanegocios.globo.com/Revista/Epocanegocios/0,,EDR82833-8374,00.html ''O legado de Lemann.''] In: ''[[Epoca Neg\u00f3cios]].'' English translation: [https://docslide.us/documents/abi-lemann-telles-article.html ''Lemann's Legacy.''] ''English Docslide'', 2015-04-08. Retrieved 2018-10-20.</ref>  He usually spends his time between [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Rapperswil SG|Rapperswil-Jona]] on [[Lake Zurich]],<ref name=\"HZ\" /> where his family lives, and [[St. Louis]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/jorge-paulo-lemann/ |title=Jorge Paulo Lemann |work=Forbes |date= |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzz.ch/aktuell/wirtschaft/wirtschaftsnachrichten/banker-braumeister-und-burgerketten-besitzer-1.17859828 |title=Multimilliard\u00e4r Jorge Paulo Lemann: Banker, Braumeister und Burgerketten-Besitzer - NZZ |publisher=Nzz.ch |date=2012-11-30 |accessdate=2015-09-26}}</ref> \n\nIn 1999, several gunmen attempted to kidnap his children on their way to school.<ref name=\":1\" /> The incident prompted Lemann to relocate permanently to Switzerland.<ref name=\":1\" /> According to a report,\" his children still attended school that day and Lemann was only a little late to the office.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.worldfinance.com/strategy/the-rise-and-rise-of-jorge-paulo-lemann|title=The rise and rise of Jorge Paulo Lemann|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nLemann rarely gives interviews or appears publicly, and is little known in the United States.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-08-29/jorge-lemann-he-is-dot-the-worlds-most-interesting-billionaire|title=Jorge Lemann: He Is ... the World's Most Interesting Billionaire|date=2013-08-30|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref> However, according to Bloomberg, in Brazil, Lemann is considered a \"business-class hero\", \"the wiry, white-haired conglomerateur who\u2019s part Buffett, part Sam Walton, part Roger Federer.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n<!-- <ref name=\"Billionaires 2010\">{{cite news\n  |title= The World's Billionaires (2011): #55 Jorge Paulo Lemann\n  |url= https://www.forbes.com/profile/jorge-paulo-lemann\n  |work= [[Forbes]] |date= March 3, 2010 |accessdate= February 24, 2011}}\n</ref> -->\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090916033210/http://www.latinbusinesschronicle.com/app/section.aspx?id=323 Latin America's most important businessmen]. ''Latin Business Chronicle''.\n* [http://latinvex.com/app/article.aspx?id=530&g=1 Brazil's Top 50 Businesspeople]. ''Latinvex''.\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Davis Cup player}}\n\n{{Anheuser-Busch InBev}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lemann, Jorge Paulo}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Rio de Janeiro (city)]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:Swiss people of Brazilian descent]]\n[[Category:Brazilian bankers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in brewing]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Swiss male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Brazilian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Swiss billionaires]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Anheuser\u2013Busch InBev people]]\n", "name_user": "Jojo1478", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added to his description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jorge_Paulo_Lemann"}
{"title_page": "Vineet Kothari", "text_new": "{{short description|Judge of Madras High Court}}\n{{one source|date=September 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox Judge\n|name=Vineet Kothari\n|office=[[Judge]] of [[Madras High Court]]\n|termstart=23 November 2018\n|termend=\n|appointer=[[Ram Nath Kovind]]\n|nominator=[[Ranjan Gogoi]]\n|office1=[[Judge]] of [[Karnataka High Court]]\n|termstart1=18 April 2016\n|termend1=22 November 2018\n|appointer1=[[Pranab Mukherjee]]\n|nominator1=[[T. S. Thakur]]\n|office2=[[Judge]] of [[Rajasthan High Court]]\n|nominator2=[[Ramesh Chandra Lahoti]]\n|appointer2=[[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]]\n|termstart2=13 June 2005\n|termend2=17 April 2016\n|birth_date=2 September 1959\n|honorific_prefix=Hon'ble Justice\n}}\n'''Justice Vineet Kothari''' (born: 2 September 1959) is an Indian Judge. Presently, he is [[Judge]] of [[Madras High Court]]. He is former [[Judge]] of [[Karnataka High Court]] and [[Rajasthan High Court]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.barandbench.com|title=Justice Vineet Kothari appointed Acting Chief Justice of Madras High Court|last=Emmanuel|first=Meera|date=21 September 2019|work=Bar & Bench|access-date=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe born in a [[Jainism|Jain]] family of chartered accountants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mycastory.cajobportal.com/mycastory-com-dr-justice-vineet-kothari-judge-rajasthan-high-court/|title=@mycastory.com: Dr.Justice Vineet Kothari Judge, Rajasthan High Court|date=2015-03-05|website=#mycastory|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> He completed B.Com.(Hons.) from Jodhpur university in 1978. After practising as an chartered accountant for 26 years, he served with distinction the Income Tax Appellate Tribunal for 15 years from 1989 to 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/justice-vineet-kothari-to-perform-duties-of-chief-justice-of-madras-hc/article29475207.ece|title=Justice Vineet Kothari to perform duties of Chief Justice of Madras HC|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kothari, Vinery}}\n[[Category:21st-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Madras High Court]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Judge of Madras High Court}}\n{{one source|date=September 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox Judge\n|name=Vineet Kothari\n|office=[[Judge]] of [[Madras High Court]]\n|termstart=23 November 2018\n|termend=\n|appointer=[[Ram Nath Kovind]]\n|nominator=[[Ranjan Gogoi]]\n|office1=[[Judge]] of [[Karnataka High Court]]\n|termstart1=18 April 2016\n|termend1=22 November 2018\n|appointer1=[[Pranab Mukherjee]]\n|nominator1=[[T. S. Thakur]]\n|office2=[[Judge]] of [[Rajasthan High Court]]\n|nominator2=[[Ramesh Chandra Lahoti]]\n|appointer2=[[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]]\n|termstart2=13 June 2005\n|termend2=17 April 2016\n|birth_date=2 September 1959\n|honorific_prefix=Hon'ble Justice\n}}\n'''Justice Vineet Kothari''' (born: 2 September 1959) is an Indian Judge. Presently, he is [[Judge]] of [[Madras High Court]]. He is former [[Judge]] of [[Karnataka High Court]] and [[Rajasthan High Court]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.barandbench.com|title=Justice Vineet Kothari appointed Acting Chief Justice of Madras High Court|last=Emmanuel|first=Meera|date=21 September 2019|work=Bar & Bench|access-date=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe born in a [[Jainism|Jain]] family of chartered accountants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mycastory.cajobportal.com/mycastory-com-dr-justice-vineet-kothari-judge-rajasthan-high-court/|title=@mycastory.com: Dr.Justice Vineet Kothari Judge, Rajasthan High Court|date=2015-03-05|website=#mycastory|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> He completed B.Com.(Hons.) from Jodhpur university in 1978. After practising as an chartered accountant for 26 years , he served with distinction the Income Tax Appellate Tribunal for 15 years from 1989 to 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/justice-vineet-kothari-to-perform-duties-of-chief-justice-of-madras-hc/article29475207.ece|title=Justice Vineet Kothari to perform duties of Chief Justice of Madras HC|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kothari, Vinery}}\n[[Category:21st-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Madras High Court]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n\n{{India-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vineet_Kothari"}
